<div id="review_2007323110" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2007323110" />
    <a title="Graychin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1013182-graychin"><img alt="Graychin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618434748p2/1013182.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2007323110?book_show_action=true">May 22, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Graychin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Graychin" href="/user/show/1013182-graychin">Graychin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2007323110" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8992781726941395581">I made my way slowly through the <i>Discourses</i> over the past six months or so. It&apos;s Roman-era self-help literature of the best sort – but that’s what philosophy was to the ancients: a guide for living, not an exercise in logic or intellectual abstraction. Our own age (an era in which victimhood is virtue and affluence is happiness) could do with a bit of the old Stoicism. It’s summarized more succinctly in Epictetus’s brief <i>Enchiridion</i> than in the <i>Discourses</i> or by the more sophisticated Marcus Aure</span>
  <span id="freeText8992781726941395581" style="display:none">I made my way slowly through the <i>Discourses</i> over the past six months or so. It's Roman-era self-help literature of the best sort – but that’s what philosophy was to the ancients: a guide for living, not an exercise in logic or intellectual abstraction. Our own age (an era in which victimhood is virtue and affluence is happiness) could do with a bit of the old Stoicism. It’s summarized more succinctly in Epictetus’s brief <i>Enchiridion</i> than in the <i>Discourses</i> or by the more sophisticated Marcus Aurelius: Accept those things that do not properly belong to you (events that occur beyond yourself, your circumstances, your reputation, even your health), since they are not in your power to control; concern yourself only with the one or two things that do belong to you – your reasoning faculty and the way you choose to react to events.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8992781726941395581" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


